eckering, Lincolnshire, England":"Holton cum Beckering, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Dexter","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (East Midlands): occupational name from Middle English <i>dexter(e)</i>, <i>dei(gh)ester</i>, <i>deyster</i> ‘dyer’ (Old English <i>deaʒestre</i>, <i>deʒ(e)stre</i>). The word originally denoted a female dyer, but came to be used for dyers of both sexes. Compare   Dyer  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dyer","meanings":["English: occupational name for a dyer of cloth, from Middle English <i>deier</i>, <i>degher</i> ‘dyer’ (Old English <i>dēag</i> ‘dye’; the verb is a back-formation from the agent noun). Compare   Dexter  . The name is typical of southern England. In the Midlands   Dexter   is the more common equivalent and in northern England   Lister  .","Irish (Sligo and Antrim): variant of   Dwyer  ."]}]},{"name":"Maude","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Maud  , the usual spelling of the name in North America."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":10,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Maude Dexter was born about 1445, in Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England. She married Rogyll Ruggles in 1469, in Holton cum Beckering, Lincolnshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died about 15